    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_3332047047" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3332047047" />
    <a title="Hai Quan" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/20274872-hai-quan"><img alt="Hai Quan" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1518929777p2/20274872.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3332047047?book_show_action=true">May 12, 2020</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Hai Quan" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Hai Quan" href="/user/show/20274872-hai-quan">Hai Quan</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/20274872-hai-quan?shelf=read-second-time">read-second-time</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/20274872-hai-quan?shelf=china">china</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3332047047" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer4066971687514139882">This is the second time I read this book.It is very well written.If you, like me, are fascinated with stories of people lives , with many twists and turns, interactions with members of one&apos;s imediate or extended family , neighbor, workplace, commune, school and most of all government officials over several centuries ......you will like this book.<br/><br/>The author has, no doubt, talked to and explored with her grand mother and her parents, particularly her mother about all the events in their lives that</span>
  <span id="freeText4066971687514139882" style="display:none">This is the second time I read this book.It is very well written.If you, like me, are fascinated with stories of people lives , with many twists and turns, interactions with members of one's imediate or extended family , neighbor, workplace, commune, school and most of all government officials over several centuries ......you will like this book.<br /><br />The author has, no doubt, talked to and explored with her grand mother and her parents, particularly her mother about all the events in their lives that happened many many years ago , even before she was born until the present time , to RECONSTRUCT her family 's five generation history starting from her great grand parents and ended with her children.<br />It is not the purpose of my review to summarise her book in detail, but only to highlight what I think are important aspects of each of her family generations:<br /><br />WOMEN FATE :<br /><br />In her great grand parents and her grand parents times all female individuals were of little social consideration and value.In these times of absolute male dominance, Confucianism social order places the King at the top, following with teachers and end with fathers.They were of course all men, women had no place in this social hierarchy.( Rare exception occured) <br />The King had absolute power over his subjects, his people, so were his courtiers, so were the fathers , who had absolute power over his descendents.<br />As the result, her great grand mother and her grand mother lives and marriages were determined by their respective fathers.<br />The power of the husband cannot be challenged , hence taking concubines by the husbands who endowed with high standing socio-economic were the norm.<br />Beside the painful and cripping foot binding, her great grand mother also were forced , with her father " consent" into being a concubine of a warlord general, leading a miserable fate of abandoned " celebrated wife - sevant " in a celebrated prison,the warlord's villa, closely watched by her maids and male servants!<br /><br />The parallel lives were that of thousands of young girls , in harems , kept within the Son Of Heaven's forbidden and forbidding , fortified , well guarded glorious compound.<br /><br />Women in all societal levels became properties, chattels to be given away or bought and sold by the male master, whoever he was.<br /><br /><br />Another sad thing that a woman endure in this era was the vicious exercise of pecking order within the harem.The wife of Kings, his courtiers , mandarins and warlords inherit the unchallenged power of their "husbands" .They were not shy to impose their powers upon their helpless and hapless victims, at all times , making the " lesser wives ", the concubines , victims of double terrorized!<br /><br />This sad fate for woman were thus thrusted upon the author's great grand mother and grand mother.It ended with her mother when the modern time came , when it was abolished by Mao' s communism.<br /><br />PEOPLE FATE UNDER COMMUNISM<br /><br />For generations, and in particular , under Manchu dynasty ( Manchu actually has conquered Chinese Han dynasty, thus a foreigner dominating power) the King/ Emperor excerted total power upon their subjects.All Chinese people are victims of their vicious taxation and other predatory social policy .The King, his courtiers, and when his power was weak, the local warlords shared with him their powers of exploiting and terrorizing their subject with the backing of their own militia forces<br /><br />All common people of course her great grand parents and her grand parents included were under their King's and warlords ' mercies.<br /><br />In this environ, her great grand parents and her grand parents chugged along, the sociery biggies , the society powefuls , the big landlords enjoyed, the population, the victims ( they didn't realise such) suffered unknowingly.<br /><br />Then came Kuomintang headed by that laughable General Chang kai-sek with his ragtag army.Many Chinese overjoyed with the demise of Manchu dynasty.But their joy was short lived .Their liberator , their rescuer was not much better than their predecessor, their Manchu oppressor , warlords and bandits.<br />They possessed low moral and morale, low displicine, low ethical standard, low motivation in resisting Japan invader, very corrupt and decadent .<br /><br />One incident stood out: Newly arrived after the Japan's surrender ( to Western forces) the Kuomintang army officers were scrambling to get themseves local concubines ! ( Jung Chang's mother resisted one such attempt!)<br /><br />Not much surprisingly afterward, the US backed Kuomintang ( ** 2) fled after Mao's communist overtaking.<br />The author 's father , under her pen, appeared to be an exemplify model of a communist who withold Mao 's communist principle steadfastly : the abolishment of all old feudal vicious unequal societal , governmental, organisational corruptional and social order <br /><br />Many times, he resisted to excersise favouritism within his family member , including his own wife for special treatment as his high position could have been afforded.<br />In one incident, he refused his wife to ride with him in his car while their unit was moving to a new location because he said it was against regulation, unbeknownst to him: his wife was expecting her ( and his) first baby, was bleeding, resulting in an abortion !<br /><br />There were several cases afterward that showed his steadfast adherent to incorruptibility.He wanted to be the beacon for communism , for his party's endevour of complete divorcing from the ills of China's feudal past .<br />( It is a great pity, despite Jung family, especially her father devotion to the communist noble cause, they were all persecuted repeatedly by mob " justice" encouraged by that egomaniacal and delusional half God Mao and his crazed personal cultists with numerous " struggle" meetings , labor camps etc....TOGETHER with many people at all social and political levels and party hierarchy.This was the darkest period in modern China history)<br /><br />The initial result:<br /><br />Gone were emperor, warlords, big landowners, their concubines , their enormous wealth , their vicious taxation, their cut-throat lending practice, their terrorism upon their subjects ( their chattels), the population in general.<br /><br />Land were divided to the tillers.Factories were owned collectively by the government workers.Housing and salary were supplied to all government officials.<br /><br />Kuomingtang fled to Taiwan!<br /><br />Alas, this rosy period didn't last long.Mao's regime, and so was Jung Chang family were plunged down hill into numerous upheavals with Mao's paranoid filled, untested and unfathomable , unrealistic, unscientific social, political , economical "policies" that brought riots, complete chaos, a screeching halt to all progress, a total colapse of everything.!<br /><br />Too bad!, Mao has advanced his China one step ahead only to push it back ten steps backward!<br /><br />Thus was the fate of Jung Chang immediate and extended family.<br />Until the last part of her book , with the demise of that devil -clown head of state and his actress-wife scoundrel and the re-emergence of his younger and sane former comrades, peace ,order and meaningful , more open, more realisric , more sane , more scientific social and economical policies were restored , resulting in today China, her family included.<br /><br />Her story is well told, in minutes details, of all of her family members, their friends and relatives.Her painstaking narrative lead her readers into the deepest inner corners of numerous characters , giving you a rich landscape of humanity in its threshold between the ancient past and the new emerged modern century.<br /><br />It makes you cry and laugh.It makes you sad, angry , frustrated ,troubled with tragedies but also makes you overjoyed, enlighten and believing in human unbeatable spirit under the most trying circumstances.<br /><br />Must I say if I recommend this book to you? <br /><br /><br />Written @ coronatime.com<br />We will overcome together<br /><br /><br />.</span>
  <a data-text-id="4066971687514139882" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


